ity of the CIA's use of "enhanced interrogation." By the end of the Bush administration, members of both major congressional parties had come to denounce enhanced interrogation as torture and argue for the closing of Guantánamo. What initiated this shift? In Talking About Torture, Jared Del Rosso reviews transcripts from congressional hearings and scholarship on denial, torture, and state violence to document this wholesale change in rhetoric and attitude toward the use of torture by the CIA and the U.S. military during the War on Terror. He plots the evolution of the "torture issue" in U.S. politics and its manipulation by politicians to serve various ends. Most important, Talking About Torture integrates into the debate about torture the testimony of those who suffered under American interrogation practices and demonstrates how the conversation continues to influence current counterterrorism policies, such as the reliance on drones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExtraordinary renditionxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aTorturexGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aTorturexPolitical aspects. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 70(DE-588)4013943-80(DE-627)1046538920(DE-576)208906053aEinstellung2gnd 70(DE-588)4017801-80(DE-627)1063286970(DE-576)208921141aFolter2gnd 70(DE-588)4059534-10(DE-627)1061432120(DE-576)209131136aTerrorismus2gnd 70(DE-588)4063099-70(DE-627)1061291040(DE-576)209147334aVernehmung2gnd 70(DE-588)4076217-80(DE-627)1060834220(DE-576)209201207aPolitische Einstellung2gnd 70(DE-588)4112701-80(DE-627)1043216790(DE-576)209470127aBekämpfung2gnd 70(DE-588)4173376-90(DE-627)1053804660(DE-576)209949767aParlamentsdebatte2gnd 70(DE-588)4276272-80(DE-627)1044234200(DE-576)210723971aMenschenrechtsverletzung2gnd 70(DE-588)4360006-20(DE-627)1813081690(DE-576)21